      "acceptanceCriteria": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is a commercially validated solver; internal SQA documentation (IQ/OQ/PQ) on file. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is used under an active commercial license with documented installation qualification, operational qualification, and performance qualification records. Solver benchmarks against NAFEMS LE1 and LE10 plate problems pass within 0.5%. SQA documentation is maintained under document control system DC-FEA-2022."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Solver benchmark problems (patch test, beam bending, Hertzian contact) must reproduce analytical solutions within 1%. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "Three benchmark problems were executed: (1) patch test for 3-D solid elements passes to machine precision; (2) cantilever beam bending with SOLID186 elements reproduces Euler-Bernoulli deflection within 0.3%; (3) Hertzian contact between sphere and flat reproduces analytical peak pressure within 0.8%. All benchmarks documented in verification report VR-CODE-2022-01."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study using GCI method; GCI < 5% for all QoIs at production mesh density. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "A four-level mesh refinement study was performed on the non-cannulated 7.5 mm construct model. Richardson extrapolation-based GCI values at the production mesh (0.4 mm global element size) are 2.1% for stiffness, 2.8% for yield force, and 3.4% for peak von Mises stress — all below the 5% threshold. Monotonic convergence confirmed. The mesh convergence study was conducted as described in verification plan VP-NONCANN-001 and is summarized in the verification activity record; GCI tabular outputs are discussed in the activity description but no formal evidence artifact in this package carries prov:wasGeneratedBy pointing to the mesh convergence activity IRI."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative solver residuals < 1e-6 for all load steps; no unconverged substeps. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "All nonlinear quasi-static load steps converged with force residual norm below 1e-6. No bisection events occurred. Solver output logs archived under model record MR-NONCANN-001. Contact stabilization energy monitored and confirmed below 1% of total strain energy across all load steps."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Independent peer review of model setup, boundary conditions, and material assignments by a second qualified analyst. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "An independent review of the FEA model setup was conducted by a second senior analyst not involved in model construction. Boundary conditions (fixed base plate, load applied at superior vertebral body fixture), material assignments (Ti-6Al-4V: E=114 GPa, σ_y=880 MPa; UHMWPE blocks: E=1.0 GPa), and contact definitions were verified against the physical test setup and ASTM F1717 standard. No discrepancies identified. Review documented in peer review checklist PRC-NONCANN-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Justification of constitutive model choice; comparison of model form assumptions against physical behavior observed in experiments. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "Bilinear isotropic hardening (BISO) plasticity is used for Ti-6Al-4V based on uniaxial tensile coupon data. The UHMWPE vertebral body simulants are modeled as linear elastic, consistent with the small-strain regime observed in F1717 testing. Frictional contact (μ=0.2) at screw-rod interface is justified by literature values for Ti-Ti interfaces. Model form assumptions are consistent with observed experimental load-displacement behavior (linear stiffness phase, yield plateau)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from traceable measurements or certified material datasheets; geometric inputs verified against CMM measurements. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V material properties (E, σ_y, tangent modulus) sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing (N=5 coupons per lot, two lots). UHMWPE block properties from supplier datasheet with independent verification testing. Screw and rod geometry verified against CMM measurements of production hardware (tolerance ±0.01 mm). All input data archived in dataset DS-INPUTS-NONCANN-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "N≥10 experimental constructs; samples representative of production hardware; dimensional inspection documented. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "N=11 non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested across two independent laboratories (Lab A: N=6, Lab B: N=5). All constructs assembled from production-representative hardware with full dimensional inspection. Coefficient of variation for construct stiffness across labs: 4.2%. Sample documentation archived in test report TR-F1717-NONCANN-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of COU operating conditions; at minimum two load levels or two environmental conditions evaluated. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single load configuration (standard ASTM F1717 compression-bending at 5°/7° angulation) and ambient temperature only. The COU encompasses only this single test condition; however, the ASME V&V 40 factor requires at least two distinct test conditions to achieve Gradation 3. This factor is below required level and is a noted limitation of the current validation campaign. A risk-informed decision was made to accept this gap given the medium model risk level and the strong agreement observed across other QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs (geometry, material properties, BCs) demonstrably matched to experimental conditions; traceability documented. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "FEA model inputs were matched to measured experimental conditions: (1) screw and rod geometry from CMM measurements of test articles; (2) material properties from lot-specific coupon data; (3) fixture geometry and boundary conditions from laboratory drawings and photographs; (4) applied displacement rate equivalent to quasi-static assumption verified by kinetic energy ratio < 1% of internal energy. Input equivalency matrix documented in IEQ-NONCANN-001."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (percent difference and E/uval) computed for all QoIs; all metrics within pre-specified acceptance bounds. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "Three QoIs compared: construct stiffness (1.6% difference, E/uval=0.41), yield force (2.3%, E/uval=0.78), force at 40 mm (1.0%, E/uval=0.29). All within pre-specified bounds of <10% and E/uval<1.96. Validation uncertainty (uval) computed per ASME V&V 20 combining experimental measurement uncertainty and model parameter uncertainty via Monte Carlo sampling (N=1000 runs). Full comparison documented in validation report VR-COMPARE-NONCANN-2024."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs used in validation are directly mapped to QoIs used in the regulatory submission claim; mapping documented. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "The three validation QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are identical to the QoIs cited in the 510(k) predicate comparison and the design verification test protocol. The mapping from validation QoIs to submission claims is documented in QoI traceability matrix QTM-NONCANN-001, reviewed and approved by the regulatory affairs team."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario (geometry, loading, boundary conditions) is representative of the COU; differences between validation and COU scenarios are documented and their impact assessed. Achieved level must equal or exceed required.",
      "rationale": "The validation scenario replicates the COU directly: same screw design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm), same loading mode (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), same construct configuration (two-screw, one-rod, UHMWPE vertebral body simulants). The validation is not a surrogate scenario but a direct replication of the regulatory test. Relevance is therefore high; no bridging argument is required. Documented in validation plan VP-NONCANN-001 Section 4.2."
    }
